373","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1331–Female":"1331–Overleden","1302":"1302","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","Abt 1331":"circa 1331","1331":"1331","1373":"1373","Bramshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Chebsey, Staffordshire, England":"Chebsey, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1331–":"about 1331–Deceased","1302–1373":"1302–1373","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1331–Female":"1331–Deceased","1302":"1302","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","Abt 1331":"about 1331","1331":"1331","1373":"1373","Bramshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Chebsey, Staffordshire, England":"Chebsey, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stafford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name principally from Stafford (Staffordshire), but occasionally from other places with similar names, such as Stafford House in Ifield (Sussex), possibly East and West Stowford in East Down (Devon), and three minor places in Devon called Stafford, in Dolton, Broadhembury, and Colyton parishes. The places are all named with Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’ as the final element, but have different initial elements. The Staffordshire placename has Old English <i>stæth</i> ‘river bank, shore’; Stafford in Colyton (Devon) has Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’; the Sussex placename has Old English <i>stēor</i> ‘steer, bullock’; East and West Stowford (Devon) have Old English <i>stæf</i> ‘staff, stave, rod’; Stafford in Dolton and Stafford in Broadhembury (Devon) may have Old English <i>stæth</i>, <i>stān</i>, or <i>stæf</i>.","Irish (Wexford): variant of   Stocker  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stocker","meanings":["German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>): topographic name for someone living by a tree stump (see   Stock   3) or an occupational name for a tree cutter, from Middle High German <i>stocken</i> ‘to clear land’.","German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>); Dutch: occupational name from Middle High German, Middle Dutch <i>stocker</i> ‘jailer’.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>stokker</i> ‘one who sells stockfish’ (fish dried in the air without salt). This was the usual source of the name in medieval London, where a bylaw of 1419 stated that no <i>stokker</i> should board a ship to buy fish (presumably in order to forestall the market)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Stafford was born about 1331. She had at least 1 son with John de Stafford. She died in Bramshall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1331–":"umbes 1331–Surnud","1302–1373":"1302–1373","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1331–Female":"1331–Surnud","1302":"1302","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","Abt 1331":"umbes 1331","1331":"1331","1373":"1373","Bramshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chebsey, Staffordshire, England":"Chebsey, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1331–":"noin 1331–Kuollut","1302–1373":"1302–1373","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1331–Female":"1331–Kuollut","1302":"1302","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","Abt 1331":"noin 1331","1331":"1331","1373":"1373","Bramshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Chebsey, Staffordshire, England":"Chebsey, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1331–":"environ 1331–Décédée","1302–1373":"1302–1373","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1331–Female":"1331–Décédée","1302":"1302","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","Abt 1331":"environ 1331","1331":"1331","1373":"1373","Bramshall, Staffordshire, Engla